{"title_page": "MAT-49", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=December 2010}}\n{{Infobox weapon\n|name=Pistolet-Mitrailleur de 9 mm mod\u00e8le 1949<br>(MAT-49)\n| image= MAT Submachine Gun.jpg\n|caption= MAT-49 on display. This weapon has the front grip lowered in firing position, but lacks a magazine.\n|type=[[Submachine gun]]\n|service=1949\u2013present\n|wars=[[First Indochina War]]<br>[[Suez Crisis]]<br>[[1958 Lebanon Crisis]]<br>[[Algerian War]]<br>[[Vietnam War]]<br>[[Laotian Civil War]]<br>[[Cambodian Civil War]]<br>[[Portuguese Colonial War]]<br>[[Rhodesian Bush War]]<br>[[Western Sahara War]]<br>[[Shaba II]]<br>[[Chadian\u2013Libyan conflict]]<br>[[Lebanese Civil War]]<br>[[2011 Libyan Civil War|Libyan Civil War]]<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/04/21/world/africa/21rebels.html?pagewanted=all | work=The New York Times | first=C. J. | last=Chivers | title=Inferior Arms Hobble Rebels in Libya War | date=April 20, 2011}}</ref><br>[[Syrian Civil War]]<br>[[Northern Mali conflict]]<ref>{{cite report|title= Rebel Forces in Northern Mali: Documented weapons, ammunition and related materiel, April 2012-March 2013|publisher = [[Conflict Armament Research]] and [[Small Arms Survey]]|date= April 2013|url=http://www.conflictarm.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Rebel_Forces_in_Northern_Mali.pdf }}</ref><br>[[Central African Republic Civil War (2012\u2013present)]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Importante saisie d'armes en Centrafrique|newspaper=[[Radio France Internationale|RFI]]|date=16 March 2014|url=http://www.rfi.fr/afrique/20140315-importante-saisie-armes-centrafrique-rca-misca|language=fr}}</ref>\n|designer=Pierre Monteil\n|manufacturer=[[Manufacture Nationale d'Armes de Tulle]] <br> [[Manufacture d'armes de Saint-\u00c9tienne]]\n|length=460 mm (18.1 inch)<br>720 mm (28.3 in)\n|action=[[Blowback (arms)|Blowback]], [[open bolt]]\n|is_ranged=yes\n| image_size = 300\n|origin= France\n|era=Post 1945\n|platform=Individual\n|target=Personnel\n|design_date=1949\n|production_date=1949\u20131979\n|used_by=See ''[[MAT-49#Users|Users]]''\n|spec_type=\n|caliber=9 mm\n|part_length={{convert|230|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n|cartridge=[[9\u00d719mm Parabellum]]<br>[[7.62\u00d725mm Tokarev]] (VPA converted)\n|feed=20 or 32 rounds<br>35 rounds (VPA converted)\n|rate=600 rounds per minute<ref name=\"modernfirearms\">http://world.guns.ru/smg/fr/mat-49-e.html</ref>\n|velocity=\n|weight={{convert|3.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}} without magazine<br>{{convert|4.2|kg|lb|abbr=on}} with 32-round magazine\n|variants= See [[MAT-49#Variants|Variants]]\n}}\n\nThe '''MAT-49''' was a [[submachine gun]] which was developed by French arms factory Manufacture Nationale d'Armes de Tulle (MAT) for use by the [[French Army]] and was first produced in 1949.\n\n==Development==\nIn 1949, after evaluating several prototypes (including a collapsible design from [[Hotchkiss et Cie|Hotchkiss]]), the French MAT factory began production of the MAT-49 9&nbsp;mm submachine gun. The MAT-49 used a [[Stamping (metalworking)|machine stamping process]] which allowed the economical production of large numbers of submachine guns, then urgently required by the French Government for use by Army, [[French Foreign Legion]] as well as airborne and colonial forces.\n\nProduction continued at Tulle until the mid-1960s, then switched to the [[Manufacture d'armes de Saint-\u00c9tienne]] plant (MAS), where the weapon was produced until 1979. In that same year, the French armed forces adopted the [[FAMAS]] [[5.56\u00d745mm NATO|5.56 mm NATO]] [[assault rifle]], and the MAT-49 was gradually phased out of service in favor of the bullpup FAMAS\n\n==Usage==\n[[File:Mortier2.jpg|thumb|right|Paratroopers of the [[2nd Foreign Parachute Regiment|2e REP]] storming [[Kolwezi]] in 1978]]\nThe MAT-49 saw widespread combat use during the [[First Indochina War]] and the [[Algerian War]], as well as the 1956 [[Suez Crisis]].<ref name=\"SA\">http://www.smallarmsreview.com/display.article.cfm?idarticles=2508</ref><ref name=\"LEU\">Leulliette, Pierre, ''St. Michael and the dragon;: Memoirs of a paratrooper'', New York:Houghton, Mifflin & Co. (1964), p. 29</ref> The weapon found considerable favor with airborne and mechanized troops, who prized it for its simplicity, ruggedness, firepower and compactness.<ref name=\"LEU\"/>\n\nAfter French forces left [[Indochina]], the [[Vietnam People's Army|People's Army of Vietnam]] and [[Viet Minh]] converted many captured MAT-49s to the Soviet [[7.62\u00d725mm Tokarev|7.62 mm Tokarev]] pistol cartridge, then available in large quantities from the [[Soviet Union]] and the [[People's Republic of China]]. These converted versions could be distinguished by a longer barrel and a higher rate of fire at 900 rpm.<ref name=\"5RAR\">http://www.5rar.asn.au/weapons/mat49.htm</ref><ref>http://www.virginia1774.org/DIA-ST-HB-07-03-74.pdf</ref>\n\nNorth Vietnam covertly provided MAT-49s to anti-French occupation groups during the Algerian War after the French left Indochina.<ref>https://www.forgottenweapons.com/vietnamese-guns-for-algeria/</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe MAT-49 had a short, retractable wire stock, which when extended gave the weapon a length of {{convert|720|mm|in|abbr=on}}, and the magazine well and magazine could be folded forward parallel to the barrel for parachute jump or with a 45\u00b0 angle hence allowing a safe carry until the magazine well is brought back to vertical position before opening fire. Barrel length is {{convert|230|mm|in|abbr=on}}, with some police-issue weapons manufactured with extended barrels and non-retractable wooden stocks. As issued, the MAT-49 fires a [[9\u00d719mm Parabellum]] cartridge, using a single-column 20-round magazine for desert use or 32-round similar to the [[Sten]] magazine.\n\nThe MAT-49 is [[Blowback (arms)|blowback]]-operated and box magazine-fed, with a rate of fire of 600 rounds per minute on full auto. The MAT 49/54, a modified MAT-49s manufactured for police forces, had two triggers, allowing use of full-auto fire or single shots, but most were manufactured as full-auto only. Minus magazine, the MAT-49 weighs about {{convert|3.5|kg|lb|abbr=off}}, which renders it somewhat heavy for a submachine gun. The weapon incorporates a [[grip safety]] which is located on the backside of the pistol grip. The rear sights are flip-up and \"L\"-shaped, and marked for a range of {{convert|50|and|100|m|yds|sp=us}}. Production ceased after the introduction of the [[FAMAS]] assault rifle in 1979.\n\n==Variants==\n*[[MAS-48]] - prototype variant.\n*MAT-49 - main variant.\n*MAT-49/54 - gendarme variant with extended barrel and fixed stock.\n*MAT-49 silenced - variant fitted with a [[suppressor]].<ref name=\"SA\"/>\n*K-43 (or MAT-49 M) - variant modified by the [[Viet Minh]], firing in [[7.62\u00d725mm Tokarev]]. It had a longer barrel and a higher rate of fire (900 rpm). Spare parts were still produced in the 1970s, the gun being used by the guerilla [[Viet Cong]].<ref name=\"Vietnam\">{{cite book|title=Personal firepower|first=Edward Clinton|last= Ezell|publisher=Bantam Books|year=1988|series=The Illustrated history of the Vietnam War 15|oclc=1036801376|url=https://archive.org/details/personalfirepowe00ezel|url-access=registration|pages=[https://archive.org/details/personalfirepowe00ezel/page/18 18], 35, 42}}</ref>\n<gallery>\nFile:MAT-49.svg|MAT-49: left and right views; view with stock retracted and magazine in safe position\nFile:MAT-49 54.svg|Police MAT-49/54 model\n</gallery>\n\n==Users==\n<!--READ FIRST: This section is for cited entries only. Please do not add entries into this list without a citation from a reliable source. All entries without a citation will be removed. Thank you.-->\n[[File:Togolese naval honour guard 070521.jpg|thumb|[[Togolese Armed Forces#Navy|Togolese sailors]] equipped with MAT-49 in 2007.]]\n*{{flag|Algeria}}<ref name=\"jones2009\">Jones, Richard D. ''Jane's Infantry Weapons 2009/2010''. Jane's Information Group; 35 edition (January 27, 2009