MDb|IMDB]]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/dariusshu5 Darius Shu] on [[Instagram]]\n* [https://www.twitter.com/dariusshu Darius Shu] on [[Twitter]]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/dariusshu Darius Shu] on [[Facebook]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shu, Darius}}\n\n[[Category: 1994 births]]\n[[Category:English cinematographers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Film directors from London]]\n[[Category:Writers from London]]\n[[Category:People from London]]\n[[Category:British cinematographers]]\n", "name_user": "Kg668", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darius_Shu"}
{"title_page": "David Robert Grimes", "text_new": "A very very nice man who is believer of sciency stuff {{short description|Irish science writer (born 1985)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n\n[[File:David Robert Grime Portrait.jpg|alt=|thumb|David Robert Grimes, 2018]]\n'''David Robert Grimes''' (born 1985{{citation needed lead|date=December 2019}}) is an Irish science writer with professional training in [[physics]] and [[oncology|cancer biology]], who contributes to several media outlets on questions of science and society. He has a diverse range of research interests, and is a vocal advocate for increased public understanding of science. He was the 2014 recipient of the [[Sense About Science]]/Nature Maddox Prize for \"Standing up for Science in the face of Adversity\".\n\n== Early life ==\nDavid Robert Grimes, from a [[Skerries, Dublin|Skerries]] family, was born in [[Dublin]] in 1985.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} Grimes spent over a decade in [[Riyadh]], Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite web| author = Lodge, Kane & D.R. Grimes | date = December 30, 2016 | title = Interviews, Science: Interview with Dr David Robert Grimes | work = [[The Freethink Tank]] [online magazine] | format = interview | url=http://www.thefreethinktank.com/interview-dr-david-robert-grimes/| accessdate = 11 December 2019}}</ref>{{third-party inline|date=December 2019}} As a student he was a keen musician and actor, with an interest in science.<ref>{{Cite news | author = Grimes, D.R. (and Peter McGuire, editor) | date = 10 January 2017 | title=Why I Became... Six Successful People Discuss Their Career Paths...| work=The Irish Times | url = https://www.irishtimes.com/news/education/why-i-became-1.2930676 | access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref>{{third-party inline|date=December 2019}} He undertook his undergraduate degree in [[applied physics]] at [[Dublin City University|DCU]], serving on the Student Union as faculty-wide Science and Health [[Convenor]] 2005\u20132006,<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www4.dcu.ie/alumni/wall.shtml|title=DCU Alumni Wall \u2013 Our 2015 Awardees {{!}} DCU|website=www4.dcu.ie|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref> and on the DCU drama committee,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redbrick.dcu.ie/~drama/committee/vice-chair.html|title=Committee Vice-Chair: DCU Drama|website=redbrick.dcu.ie|access-date=21 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018072238/https://www.redbrick.dcu.ie/~drama/committee/vice-chair.html|archive-date=18 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> graduating in 2007 with a DCU Internal School Award, the Lyman Medal for physics.<ref>{{cite web| author = DCU Staff | date = 22 November 2019  | title = School of Physical Sciences, Undergraduate Programmes, Prizes & Awards: Internal School Medal Awards, Medals for Best Overall Performances in 4th year/degree, Lynam medal | work = DCU.ie | location = Dublin, IE | publisher = Dublin City University, School of Physical Sciences | url=https://www.dcu.ie/physics/awardandsprizes.shtml|access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional biography==\n{{expand section|usual professional biographical content for a scholar, including positions and appointments, and third-party sourcing to establish notability of scientific achievements| small = no|date=December 2019}}\nGrimes did doctoral work on ultraviolet radiation physics at Dublin City University funded by an [[Irish Research Council]] award,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.research.ie/awards/embark-2007-08|title=Research.ie awards 2007\u20132008|access-date=21 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623114640/http://www.research.ie/awards/embark-2007-08|archive-date=23 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> under [[Neil O'Hare]] and [[Greg Hughes (professor)|Greg Hughes]], and graduated with a [[Ph.D.]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite thesis|url=http://doras.dcu.ie/16474/|title=Development of a radiation computation dose model for use in ultraviolet phototherapy|author=Grimes, David Robert|date=November 2011|website=doras.dcu.ie|access-date=21 July 2017|publisher=Dublin City University|type=doctoral}}</ref> He did a postdoctoral fellowship at the [[University of Oxford]] with [[Mike Partridge]], and focused on medical physics and [[oncology]],<ref>{{cite web| author = Grimes, D.R. | date = 18 January 2015 | title=Dr David Robert Grimes | format = staff webpage |location = Oxford, UK | publisher=self, University of Oxford|access-date= 11 December 2019 | url=http://users.ox.ac.uk/~donc0074/| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118191715/http://users.ox.ac.uk/~donc0074/ | archive-date=18 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{third party inline|date=December 2019}} including a 2015 research work on oxygen-radiation interactions (the \"oxygen fixation hypothesis and oxygen enhancement ratio\")<ref>{{Cite journal|title=A mechanistic investigation of the oxygen fixation hypothesis and oxygen enhancement ratio|first1=David|last1=Robert Grimes|first2=Mike|last2=Partridge|date=4 December 2015|journal=Biomedical Physics & Engineering Express|volume=1|issue=4|page=045209|doi=10.1088/2057-1976/1/4/045209|pmid=26925254|pmc=4765087}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=December 2019}}\u2014about which he blogged<ref>{{cite web|author = Grimes, D.R. | url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/news/science-blog/breath-fresh-air-%E2%80%93-shedding-light-oxygen-radiation-and-cancer-treatment|title=A Breath of Fresh Air\u2013Shedding Light on Oxygen, Radiation and Cancer Treatment | location = Oxford, UK | publisher=self, University of Oxford|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref>\u2014and literature reviews on modelling tumour oxygen distribution and [[Hypoxia (medical)|hypoxia]] in 2014<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Oxygen consumption dynamics in steady-state tumour models|first1=David Robert|last1=Grimes|first2=Alexander G.|last2=Fletcher|first3=Mike|last3=Partridge|journal= Royal Society Open Science|volume=1|issue=1|page=140080 |doi=10.1098/rsos.140080|pmid=26064525|pmc=4448765|year = 2014|bibcode = 2014RSOS....140080G}}</ref> (which received media attention<ref>{{Citation|last=The Royal Society|title=Oxygen dynamics in tumour models|date=25 September 2014|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zlXmmdk9Ovg|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>), and on non-invasive imaging in 2017.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grimes|first=D.R.|last2=Warren|first2=D.R.|last3=Warren|first3=S.|date=25 May 2017|title=Hypoxia Imaging and Radiotherapy: Bridging the Resolution Gap|journal=Brit J Radiol |volume=90 |issue=1076 |page=20160939 |doi=10.1259/bjr.20160939 |pmid=28540739|pmc=5603947 |issn=0007-1285}}</ref>{{third-party inline|date=December 2019}}\n\nAs of January 2018, Grimes had worked with [[Centre for Advanced and Interdisciplinary Radiation Research]] (CAIRR), and the School of Mathematics and Physics, [[Queen\u2019s University Belfast]], in [[Belfast]], United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Access to HPV vaccination for boys in the United Kingdom|first1=Gillian|last1=Prue|first2=David|last2=Grimes|first3=Peter|last3=Baker|first4=Mark|last4=Lawler|date=1 January 2018|journal=Medicine Access @ Point of Care|volume=2|pages=2399202618799691|doi=10.1177/2399202618799691|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Observation of dose-rate dependence in a Fricke dosimeter irradiated at low dose rates with monoenergetic X-rays|first1=Mel|last1=O\u2019Leary|first2=Daria|last2=Boscolo|first3=Nicole|last3=Breslin|first4=Jeremy M. C.|last4=Brown|first5=Igor P.|last5=Dolbnya|first6=Chris|last6=Emerson|first7=Catarina|last7=Figueira|first8=Oliver J. L.|last8=Fox|first9=David Robert|last9=Grimes|first10=Vladimir|last10=Ivosev|first11=Annette K.|last11=Kleppe|first12=Aaron|last12=McCulloch|first13=Ian|last13=Pape|first14=Chris|last14=Polin|first15=Nathan|last15=Wardlow|first16=Fred J.|last16=Currell|date=16 March 2018|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=8|issue=1|pages=4735|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-21813-z|bibcode=2018NatSR...8.4735O|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Oxygen diffusion in ellipsoidal tumour spheroids|first1=David Robert|last1=Grimes|first2=Frederick J.|last2=Currell|date=31 August 2018|journal=Journal of the Royal Society Interface|volume=15|issue=145|pages=20180256 |doi=10.1098/rsif.2018.0256|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://pure.qub.ac.uk/en/publications/a-dangerous-balancing-act-on-matters-of-science-a-well-meaning-de |title=A dangerous balancing act: On matters of science, a well-meaning desire to present all views equally can be an Trojan horse for damaging falsehoods \u2014 Queen's University Belfast |journal=EMBO Reports |volume=20 |issue=8 |doi=10.15252/embr.201948706 |publisher=Pure.qub.ac.uk |date=2019-07-09 |accessdate=2019-12-12|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n===Other research interests===\nHe has a number of other research interests, including with regard to dubious beliefs in general; a 2016 research analysis of common scientific conspiracy claims was performed using a [[Poisson distribution|Poisson]] statistical framework.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grimes|first=D.R.|date=26 January 2016|title=On the Viability of Conspiratorial Beliefs|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=11|issue=1|pages=e0147905|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147905|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4728076|pmid=26812482|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147905G}}</ref> The work suggests that massive conspiracies should quickly collapse, and was widely covered in the media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-35411684|title=Maths study shows conspiracies 'prone to unravelling'|last=Berezow|first=Alex|date=26 January 2016|work=BBC News|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=December 2019}} His writing includes consideration of dubious medical practices, including a 2012 review piece critical of [[Homeopathy|homoeopathic]] claims, presented from a physics perspective.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grimes|first=D.R.|date=1 September 2012|title=Proposed Mechanisms for Homeopathy are Physically Impossible|journal=Focus Altern Complement Ther | volume=17 |issue=3 | pages=149\u2013155 |doi=10.1111/j.2042-7166.2012.01162.x|issn=2042-7166 }}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=December 2019}}\n\nHe is also the author of a 2014 research study on the physics of string-bending that occurs during electric guitar playing,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grimes|first=D.R.|date=23 July 2014|title=String Theory\u2013The Physics of String-Bending and Other Electric Guitar Techniques|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=9|issue=7|pages=e102088|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0102088|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4108333|pmid=25054880|bibcode=2014PLoSO...9j2088G}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=December 2019}} which was covered extensively in the media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/news/2014-07-24-physics-lead-guitar-playing|title=The physics of lead guitar playing {{!}} University of Oxford|publisher=University of Oxford|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n== Science outreach ==\nGrimes is best known for science journalism and outreach, and has contributed to numerous publications, including [[The Irish Times|''Irish Times'']],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/search/search-7.1213540?q=david+robert+grimes&writerName=David+Robert+Grimes|title=Search|website=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/david-robert-grimes|title=David Robert Grimes|website=The Guardian|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref> the [[BBC]], and other outlets.<ref>{{Cite news| author = Grimes, David Robert | url=https://conversation.which.co.uk/shopping/david-robert-grimes-john-maddox-prize-ask-for-evidence/|title=Conversation: Challenging Claims and Standing up for Science|date=12 November 2014|work=Which? |access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref> His pieces focus on aspects of science and society, as well as debunking [[pseudoscience]] on topics that can be controversial in the public mind, such as [[vaccination]], [[climate-change]], gun control, nuclear power, public health and scientific misconceptions.\n\nGrimes has advocated [[secularism]] in the Irish education system.<ref>{{Cite news|date = 7 May 2012 | author = Grimes, David Robert | url=http://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/evil-militant-anti-christian-secularism-is-simply-a-myth-1.516380|title=Evil, militant anti-Christian secularism is simply a myth|work=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date = 26 February 2015 | author = Grimes, David Robert | url=http://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/richard-dawkins-is-right-children-need-secular-education-where-all-rights-are-respected-1.2118435|title=Richard Dawkins is right: children need secular education, where all rights are respected|work=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref> He criticised Irish religious conservatives for misrepresenting the research on abortion and same-sex marriage for political purposes, acknowledging that, while they were entitled to ethical misgivings, their policy of \"misrepresenting research... to bolster religious views is a transparently cynical exercise\".<ref>{{Cite news|date = 29 June 2012 | author = Grimes, David Robert | url=http://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/facts-still-sacred-despite-ireland-s-spectrum-of-conflicting-views-on-abortion-1.1069528|title=Facts still sacred despite Ireland's spectrum of conflicting views on abortion|work=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date = 26 June 2013 | author = Grimes, David Robert | url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/religion-and-beliefs/strong-religious-convictions-are-no-excuse-for-misrepresenting-research-1.1442395|title=Strong religious convictions are no excuse for misrepresenting research|work=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| author = Grimes, David Robert | url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2015/aug/12/five-main-anti-abortion-arguments-examined|title=A scientist weighs up the five main anti-abortion arguments|format = blog |date=12 August 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date = 22 May 2015  | author = Grimes, David Robert | url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2015/may/22/why-the-bad-science-of-the-no-campaign-shouldnt-sway-irelands-voters|title=Why the bad science of the no campaign shouldn't sway Ireland's voters|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The piece claiming misrepresented research prompted a strong rebuttal from John Murray, also in ''[[The Irish Times]]'', that took Grimes to task, claiming various factual and interpretive errors in his piece.<ref>{{Cite news|author = Murray, John | url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/religion-and-beliefs/there-is-no-evidence-to-suggest-we-should-abandon-traditional-marriage-as-basis-of-our-society-1.1450621|date = 3 July 2013 | title=There is no evidence to suggest we should abandon traditional marriage as basis of our society|work=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref><!--<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/drinks-industry-strategy-relies-on-recruiting-young-drinkers-to-their-brand-1.1446596|title=Drinks industry strategy relies on recruiting young drinkers to their brand|work=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref>-- THIS SOURCE NEEDS ITS CONTENT DESCRIBED BEFORE IT IS REINTRODUCED.-->\n\n=== Fluoride and cannabis campaigns ===\n\nGrimes has been critical of anti-[[Fluoride therapy|fluoride]] campaigns, in particular a 2013 [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] bill to ban fluoride in water.<ref>{{Cite news|date = 4 April 2014  | author = Grimes, David Robert | url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2014/apr/04/politicians-anti-fluoridation-campaigners-fluoride-water|title=Politicians should stop pandering to anti-fluoridation campaigners|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> This stance made him the target of conspiracy theorists, and prompted a campaign to have him removed from his university post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livescience.com/53494-how-to-tell-if-conspiracy-theories-are-real.html|title=How to Tell If Conspiracy Theories Are Real: Here's the Math|last=Kubota 2016-01-27T13:07:23Z|first=Taylor|website=livescience.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> The bill was ultimately defeated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/proposal-to-end-water-fluoridation-on-health-grounds-rejected-in-d%C3%A1il-1.1588912|title=Proposal to end water fluoridation on health grounds rejected in D\u00e1il|last=O'Regan|first=Michael|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref>\n\nGrimes has also been publicly critical of a [[Medical cannabis|medicinal cannabis]] campaign by [[People Before Profit Alliance|People Before Profit]], specifically [[Panacea (medicine)|cure-all]] claims made by representatives of the campaign. He has particularly criticised dubious claims linking cannabis to cures for cancer and [[autism]],<ref>{{Cite news| author = Grimes, David Robert | url=https://life.spectator.co.uk/articles/the-rise-of-the-cannabis-cult-dont-believe-the-hype-about-medical-marijuana/|title=The rise of the cannabis cult: don't believe the hype about medical marijuana {{!}} Spectator Health|date=15 May 2017|work=Spectator Health|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref> saying that these positions are not supported by the evidence and could put patients at risk.\n\n=== Criticism of anti-vaccine movement and false balance ===\n\nGrimes has been particularly vocal against the [[anti-vaccine movement]], focusing on assertions by anti-[[HPV vaccines|HPV vaccine]] groups whose arguments, Grimes says, consist of \"anecdotes, emotive appeals and easily debunked assertions\", opining that \"lives of countless young men and women count on us being guided by evidence rather than rhetoric.\"<ref>{{Cite news| author = Grimes, David Robert  | url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2016/jan/11/why-is-there-opposition-hpv-vaccine-cervical-cancer|title=We know it's effective. So why is there opposition to the HPV vaccine ?|date=11 January 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 2016, following controversy around the film ''[[Vaxxed]]'', Grimes was drawn into a debate with former doctor [[Andrew Wakefield]] on Irish radio. Grimes later wrote of his reluctance to take part in the debate, and how providing Wakefield with any platform is [[false balance]].<ref>{{Cite news|author = Grimes, David Robert  | url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2016/nov/08/impartial-journalism-is-laudable-but-false-balance-is-dangerous|title=Impartial journalism is laudable. But false balance is dangerous|date=8 November 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He was extremely critical of the decision by [[Regent's University London|Regent's University]] to host Wakefield, explaining that \"Wakefield is a long-debunked fear merchant.\"<ref>{{Cite news|date = 16 February 2016 | author = Watson, Leon | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/02/16/disgraced-antimmr-vaccine-doctor-andrew-wakefield-gets-invitation/|title=Disgraced anti\u2011MMR vaccine doctor Andrew Wakefield gets invitation to university in London|work=The Telegraph|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nGrimes was also part of a subsequent successful campaign to have screenings of the movie pulled in both London and at the European parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/tomchivers/a-cinema-in-london-has-pulled-a-documentary-by-a-disgraced-a|title=A Cinema in London Has Pulled A Documentary by a Disgraced Anti-Vaccine Activist|last=Chivers|first=Tom|website=BuzzFeed|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://3menmakeatiger.blogspot.com/2017/02/andrew-wakefields-discredited-ideas-are.html|title=Three men make a tiger: Letter to President Tajani regarding EU parliament screening of anti-vaccine documentary 'Vaxxed'|last=Grimes|first=David Robert|date=1 February 2017|website=Three men make a tiger|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Advocating for evidence-based medicine ===\n\nGrimes has drawn attention to [[charlatan]]s who take advantage of vulnerable people using pseudoscience, particularly [[autistic]] people and cancer sufferers. Equally, he has been vocal about [[crowdfunding]] for dubious medical conditions and clinics, such as the [[Burzynski Clinic|Burzynkski clinic]] in [[Texas]], US, stating that while emotive, \"... raising money for such causes does not help sufferers one iota \u2013 it benefits only those with the audacity to push false hope at great expense.\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2016/aug/30/fundraising-appeals-for-the-desperately-ill-are-moving-but-evidence-is-crucial|title=Fundraising appeals for the desperately ill are moving, but evidence is crucial|last=Grimes|first=David Robert|date=30 August 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nGrimes has written at length about questionable treatments for conditions such as [[electromagnetic hypersensitivity]] which, the evidence suggests, is a psychological rather than physiological illness, criticising clinics who claim to offer cures for the ailment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2016/feb/17/electromagnetic-radiation-doesnt-make-you-ill-or-give-you-cancer-heres-why|title=Household electromagnetic radiation doesn't make you ill or give you cancer. Here's why|last=Grimes|first=David Robert|date=17 February 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/tomchivers/a-charity-could-face-investigation-over-its-adverts-that|title=A Charity Could Face Investigation Over Its Adverts That Claim W-iFi And Mobile Phones Make People Ill|last=Chivers|first=Tom|website=BuzzFeed|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref> Grimes has been particularly critical of homoeopathy, both in academic work and in popular press, which has led to angry responses from homoeopaths.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/homeopathy-does-not-work-beyond-a-placebo-effect-1.534500|title=Homeopathy does not work beyond a placebo effect|work=The Irish Times|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mayohomeopathy.ie/index.php/david-grimes-opinion/|title=David Robert Grimes's ignorant \"Opinion\" in Irish Times \u2013 Stephen Blendell Homeopath|date=16 May 2013|work=Stephen Blendell Homeopath|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Public understanding of science ===\n\nGrimes states that a major challenge in communicating about science is not strictly information deficit but rather ideological bias, and that motivated reasoning is a vital factor to acknowledge. To support this claim, he points to the evidence that political leanings influence whether one accepts the scientific consensus on climate-change.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/feb/05/denying-climate-change-scepticism-motivated-reasoning|title=Denying climate change isn't scepticism \u2013 it's 'motivated reasoning'|date=5 February 2014|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Similarly, he has argued, both in popular media and academically, that acceptance of nuclear power, gun control and vaccination is strongly influenced by ideological beliefs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2014/aug/29/libertarian-ideology-natural-enemy-science|title=Libertarian ideology is the natural enemy of science|last=Grimes|first=David Robert|date=29 August 2014|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grimes|first=David Robert|date=26 January 2016|title=On the Viability of Conspiratorial Beliefs|journal=PLOS ONE |volume=11 |issue=1 |pages=e0147905 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147905 |issn=1932-6203|pmc=4728076 |pmid=26812482|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147905G}}</ref> Grimes argues that overcoming our implicit biases and gaining a better understanding of the scientific method would improve our decision making and benefit both society and individuals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/the-way-we-argue-now-1.1898216|title=The way we argue now|work=The Irish Times|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/society-would-benefit-from-a-better-understanding-of-what-is-and-isn-t-science-1.1458052|title=Society would benefit from a better understanding of what is and isn't science|work=The Irish Times|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\nIn recognition of his efforts to present science despite hostility, Grimes was joint recipient of the 2014 Sense About Science / Nature Maddox Prize for standing up for science in the face of adversary,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://senseaboutscience.org/activities/2014-john-maddox-prize/|title=2014 John Maddox Prize \u2013 Sense about Science|website=senseaboutscience.org|access-date=21 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721023505/http://senseaboutscience.org/activities/2014-john-maddox-prize/|archive-date=21 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and was commended by [[Cancer Research UK]] for being \"... an excellent media ambassador for CRUK, and for his efforts to dispel misconceptions in science and medicine\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cancerresearchuk.org/sites/default/files/cruk_research-engagement-prizes_2015.pdf|title=Cancer Research UK \u2013 Research Engagement Prizes}}</ref> In 2015, he was also inducted into the Dublin City University Alumni Wall for his research and outreach work.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Published works ==\n===Popular works===\n====Books====\n* {{cite book |title=The Irrational Ape: Why Flawed Logic Puts us all at Risk and How Critical Thinking Can Save the World |first=David Robert |last=Grimes |publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]] |date=5 September 2019 |url= {{Google books|gXN5DwAAQBAJ|plainurl=yes}} |via=[[Google books]]}}\n<!--====Articles====\n*\n===Scholarly work===\n====Reviews====\n* \n====Research articles====\n*-->\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160221233502/http://users.ox.ac.uk/~donc0074/ Grimes staff page] at [[University of Oxford|Oxford]]. \n* [http://www.davidrobertgrimes.com/ Grimes's personal blog].\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grimes, David Robert}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Dublin City University]]\n[[Category:British sceptics]]\n[[Category:British physicists]]\n[[Category:Critics of alternative medicine]]\n[[Category:Irish physicists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin (city)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Irish science writer (born 1985)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=January 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2018}}\n\n[[File:David Robert Grime Portrait.jpg|alt=|thumb|David Robert Grimes, 2018]]\n'''David Robert Grimes''' (born 1985{{citation needed lead|date=December 2019}}) is an Irish science writer with professional training in [[physics]] and [[oncology|cancer biology]], who contributes to several media outlets on questions of science and society. He has a diverse range of research interests, and is a vocal advocate for increased public understanding of science. He was the 2014 recipient of the [[Sense About Science]]/Nature Maddox Prize for \"Standing up for Science in the face of Adversity\".\n\n== Early life ==\nDavid Robert Grimes, from a [[Skerries, Dublin|Skerries]] family, was born in [[Dublin]] in 1985.{{citation needed|date=December 2019}} Grimes spent over a decade in [[Riyadh]], Saudi Arabia.<ref>{{cite web| author = Lodge, Kane & D.R. Grimes | date = December 30, 2016 | title = Interviews, Science: Interview with Dr David Robert Grimes | work = [[The Freethink Tank]] [online magazine] | format = interview | url=http://www.thefreethinktank.com/interview-dr-david-robert-grimes/| accessdate = 11 December 2019}}</ref>{{third-party inline|date=December 2019}} As a student he was a keen musician and actor, with an interest in science.<ref>{{Cite news | author = Grimes, D.R. (and Peter McGuire, editor) | date = 10 January 2017 | title=Why I Became... Six Successful People Discuss Their Career Paths...| work=The Irish Times | url = https://www.irishtimes.com/news/education/why-i-became-1.2930676 | access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref>{{third-party inline|date=December 2019}} He undertook his undergraduate degree in [[applied physics]] at [[Dublin City University|DCU]], serving on the Student Union as faculty-wide Science and Health [[Convenor]] 2005\u20132006,<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www4.dcu.ie/alumni/wall.shtml|title=DCU Alumni Wall \u2013 Our 2015 Awardees {{!}} DCU|website=www4.dcu.ie|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref> and on the DCU drama committee,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.redbrick.dcu.ie/~drama/committee/vice-chair.html|title=Committee Vice-Chair: DCU Drama|website=redbrick.dcu.ie|access-date=21 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171018072238/https://www.redbrick.dcu.ie/~drama/committee/vice-chair.html|archive-date=18 October 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> graduating in 2007 with a DCU Internal School Award, the Lyman Medal for physics.<ref>{{cite web| author = DCU Staff | date = 22 November 2019  | title = School of Physical Sciences, Undergraduate Programmes, Prizes & Awards: Internal School Medal Awards, Medals for Best Overall Performances in 4th year/degree, Lynam medal | work = DCU.ie | location = Dublin, IE | publisher = Dublin City University, School of Physical Sciences | url=https://www.dcu.ie/physics/awardandsprizes.shtml|access-date=11 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Professional biography==\n{{expand section|usual professional biographical content for a scholar, including positions and appointments, and third-party sourcing to establish notability of scientific achievements| small = no|date=December 2019}}\nGrimes did doctoral work on ultraviolet radiation physics at Dublin City University funded by an [[Irish Research Council]] award,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.research.ie/awards/embark-2007-08|title=Research.ie awards 2007\u20132008|access-date=21 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170623114640/http://www.research.ie/awards/embark-2007-08|archive-date=23 June 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> under [[Neil O'Hare]] and [[Greg Hughes (professor)|Greg Hughes]], and graduated with a [[Ph.D.]] in 2011.<ref>{{cite thesis|url=http://doras.dcu.ie/16474/|title=Development of a radiation computation dose model for use in ultraviolet phototherapy|author=Grimes, David Robert|date=November 2011|website=doras.dcu.ie|access-date=21 July 2017|publisher=Dublin City University|type=doctoral}}</ref> He did a postdoctoral fellowship at the [[University of Oxford]] with [[Mike Partridge]], and focused on medical physics and [[oncology]],<ref>{{cite web| author = Grimes, D.R. | date = 18 January 2015 | title=Dr David Robert Grimes | format = staff webpage |location = Oxford, UK | publisher=self, University of Oxford|access-date= 11 December 2019 | url=http://users.ox.ac.uk/~donc0074/| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118191715/http://users.ox.ac.uk/~donc0074/ | archive-date=18 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{third party inline|date=December 2019}} including a 2015 research work on oxygen-radiation interactions (the \"oxygen fixation hypothesis and oxygen enhancement ratio\")<ref>{{Cite journal|title=A mechanistic investigation of the oxygen fixation hypothesis and oxygen enhancement ratio|first1=David|last1=Robert Grimes|first2=Mike|last2=Partridge|date=4 December 2015|journal=Biomedical Physics & Engineering Express|volume=1|issue=4|page=045209|doi=10.1088/2057-1976/1/4/045209|pmid=26925254|pmc=4765087}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=December 2019}}\u2014about which he blogged<ref>{{cite web|author = Grimes, D.R. | url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/news/science-blog/breath-fresh-air-%E2%80%93-shedding-light-oxygen-radiation-and-cancer-treatment|title=A Breath of Fresh Air\u2013Shedding Light on Oxygen, Radiation and Cancer Treatment | location = Oxford, UK | publisher=self, University of Oxford|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref>\u2014and literature reviews on modelling tumour oxygen distribution and [[Hypoxia (medical)|hypoxia]] in 2014<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Oxygen consumption dynamics in steady-state tumour models|first1=David Robert|last1=Grimes|first2=Alexander G.|last2=Fletcher|first3=Mike|last3=Partridge|journal= Royal Society Open Science|volume=1|issue=1|page=140080 |doi=10.1098/rsos.140080|pmid=26064525|pmc=4448765|year = 2014|bibcode = 2014RSOS....140080G}}</ref> (which received media attention<ref>{{Citation|last=The Royal Society|title=Oxygen dynamics in tumour models|date=25 September 2014|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zlXmmdk9Ovg|accessdate=21 July 2017}}</ref>), and on non-invasive imaging in 2017.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grimes|first=D.R.|last2=Warren|first2=D.R.|last3=Warren|first3=S.|date=25 May 2017|title=Hypoxia Imaging and Radiotherapy: Bridging the Resolution Gap|journal=Brit J Radiol |volume=90 |issue=1076 |page=20160939 |doi=10.1259/bjr.20160939 |pmid=28540739|pmc=5603947 |issn=0007-1285}}</ref>{{third-party inline|date=December 2019}}\n\nAs of January 2018, Grimes had worked with [[Centre for Advanced and Interdisciplinary Radiation Research]] (CAIRR), and the School of Mathematics and Physics, [[Queen\u2019s University Belfast]], in [[Belfast]], United Kingdom.<ref>{{Cite journal|title=Access to HPV vaccination for boys in the United Kingdom|first1=Gillian|last1=Prue|first2=David|last2=Grimes|first3=Peter|last3=Baker|first4=Mark|last4=Lawler|date=1 January 2018|journal=Medicine Access @ Point of Care|volume=2|pages=2399202618799691|doi=10.1177/2399202618799691|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Observation of dose-rate dependence in a Fricke dosimeter irradiated at low dose rates with monoenergetic X-rays|first1=Mel|last1=O\u2019Leary|first2=Daria|last2=Boscolo|first3=Nicole|last3=Breslin|first4=Jeremy M. C.|last4=Brown|first5=Igor P.|last5=Dolbnya|first6=Chris|last6=Emerson|first7=Catarina|last7=Figueira|first8=Oliver J. L.|last8=Fox|first9=David Robert|last9=Grimes|first10=Vladimir|last10=Ivosev|first11=Annette K.|last11=Kleppe|first12=Aaron|last12=McCulloch|first13=Ian|last13=Pape|first14=Chris|last14=Polin|first15=Nathan|last15=Wardlow|first16=Fred J.|last16=Currell|date=16 March 2018|journal=Scientific Reports|volume=8|issue=1|pages=4735|doi=10.1038/s41598-018-21813-z|bibcode=2018NatSR...8.4735O|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title=Oxygen diffusion in ellipsoidal tumour spheroids|first1=David Robert|last1=Grimes|first2=Frederick J.|last2=Currell|date=31 August 2018|journal=Journal of the Royal Society Interface|volume=15|issue=145|pages=20180256 |doi=10.1098/rsif.2018.0256|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://pure.qub.ac.uk/en/publications/a-dangerous-balancing-act-on-matters-of-science-a-well-meaning-de |title=A dangerous balancing act: On matters of science, a well-meaning desire to present all views equally can be an Trojan horse for damaging falsehoods \u2014 Queen's University Belfast |journal=EMBO Reports |volume=20 |issue=8 |doi=10.15252/embr.201948706 |publisher=Pure.qub.ac.uk |date=2019-07-09 |accessdate=2019-12-12|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n===Other research interests===\nHe has a number of other research interests, including with regard to dubious beliefs in general; a 2016 research analysis of common scientific conspiracy claims was performed using a [[Poisson distribution|Poisson]] statistical framework.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grimes|first=D.R.|date=26 January 2016|title=On the Viability of Conspiratorial Beliefs|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=11|issue=1|pages=e0147905|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147905|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4728076|pmid=26812482|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147905G}}</ref> The work suggests that massive conspiracies should quickly collapse, and was widely covered in the media.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/science-environment-35411684|title=Maths study shows conspiracies 'prone to unravelling'|last=Berezow|first=Alex|date=26 January 2016|work=BBC News|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=December 2019}} His writing includes consideration of dubious medical practices, including a 2012 review piece critical of [[Homeopathy|homoeopathic]] claims, presented from a physics perspective.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grimes|first=D.R.|date=1 September 2012|title=Proposed Mechanisms for Homeopathy are Physically Impossible|journal=Focus Altern Complement Ther | volume=17 |issue=3 | pages=149\u2013155 |doi=10.1111/j.2042-7166.2012.01162.x|issn=2042-7166 }}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=December 2019}}\n\nHe is also the author of a 2014 research study on the physics of string-bending that occurs during electric guitar playing,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grimes|first=D.R.|date=23 July 2014|title=String Theory\u2013The Physics of String-Bending and Other Electric Guitar Techniques|journal=PLOS ONE|volume=9|issue=7|pages=e102088|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0102088|issn=1932-6203|pmc=4108333|pmid=25054880|bibcode=2014PLoSO...9j2088G}}</ref>{{primary source inline|date=December 2019}} which was covered extensively in the media.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/news/2014-07-24-physics-lead-guitar-playing|title=The physics of lead guitar playing {{!}} University of Oxford|publisher=University of Oxford|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref>{{Additional citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n== Science outreach ==\nGrimes is best known for science journalism and outreach, and has contributed to numerous publications, including [[The Irish Times|''Irish Times'']],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/search/search-7.1213540?q=david+robert+grimes&writerName=David+Robert+Grimes|title=Search|website=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/david-robert-grimes|title=David Robert Grimes|website=The Guardian|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref> the [[BBC]], and other outlets.<ref>{{Cite news| author = Grimes, David Robert | url=https://conversation.which.co.uk/shopping/david-robert-grimes-john-maddox-prize-ask-for-evidence/|title=Conversation: Challenging Claims and Standing up for Science|date=12 November 2014|work=Which? |access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref> His pieces focus on aspects of science and society, as well as debunking [[pseudoscience]] on topics that can be controversial in the public mind, such as [[vaccination]], [[climate-change]], gun control, nuclear power, public health and scientific misconceptions.\n\nGrimes has advocated [[secularism]] in the Irish education system.<ref>{{Cite news|date = 7 May 2012 | author = Grimes, David Robert | url=http://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/evil-militant-anti-christian-secularism-is-simply-a-myth-1.516380|title=Evil, militant anti-Christian secularism is simply a myth|work=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date = 26 February 2015 | author = Grimes, David Robert | url=http://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/richard-dawkins-is-right-children-need-secular-education-where-all-rights-are-respected-1.2118435|title=Richard Dawkins is right: children need secular education, where all rights are respected|work=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref> He criticised Irish religious conservatives for misrepresenting the research on abortion and same-sex marriage for political purposes, acknowledging that, while they were entitled to ethical misgivings, their policy of \"misrepresenting research... to bolster religious views is a transparently cynical exercise\".<ref>{{Cite news|date = 29 June 2012 | author = Grimes, David Robert | url=http://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/facts-still-sacred-despite-ireland-s-spectrum-of-conflicting-views-on-abortion-1.1069528|title=Facts still sacred despite Ireland's spectrum of conflicting views on abortion|work=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date = 26 June 2013 | author = Grimes, David Robert | url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/religion-and-beliefs/strong-religious-convictions-are-no-excuse-for-misrepresenting-research-1.1442395|title=Strong religious convictions are no excuse for misrepresenting research|work=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| author = Grimes, David Robert | url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2015/aug/12/five-main-anti-abortion-arguments-examined|title=A scientist weighs up the five main anti-abortion arguments|format = blog |date=12 August 2015|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|date = 22 May 2015  | author = Grimes, David Robert | url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2015/may/22/why-the-bad-science-of-the-no-campaign-shouldnt-sway-irelands-voters|title=Why the bad science of the no campaign shouldn't sway Ireland's voters|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> The piece claiming misrepresented research prompted a strong rebuttal from John Murray, also in ''[[The Irish Times]]'', that took Grimes to task, claiming various factual and interpretive errors in his piece.<ref>{{Cite news|author = Murray, John | url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/religion-and-beliefs/there-is-no-evidence-to-suggest-we-should-abandon-traditional-marriage-as-basis-of-our-society-1.1450621|date = 3 July 2013 | title=There is no evidence to suggest we should abandon traditional marriage as basis of our society|work=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref><!--<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/social-affairs/drinks-industry-strategy-relies-on-recruiting-young-drinkers-to-their-brand-1.1446596|title=Drinks industry strategy relies on recruiting young drinkers to their brand|work=The Irish Times|access-date=21 July 2017}}</ref>-- THIS SOURCE NEEDS ITS CONTENT DESCRIBED BEFORE IT IS REINTRODUCED.-->\n\n=== Fluoride and cannabis campaigns ===\n\nGrimes has been critical of anti-[[Fluoride therapy|fluoride]] campaigns, in particular a 2013 [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] bill to ban fluoride in water.<ref>{{Cite news|date = 4 April 2014  | author = Grimes, David Robert | url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2014/apr/04/politicians-anti-fluoridation-campaigners-fluoride-water|title=Politicians should stop pandering to anti-fluoridation campaigners|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> This stance made him the target of conspiracy theorists, and prompted a campaign to have him removed from his university post.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livescience.com/53494-how-to-tell-if-conspiracy-theories-are-real.html|title=How to Tell If Conspiracy Theories Are Real: Here's the Math|last=Kubota 2016-01-27T13:07:23Z|first=Taylor|website=livescience.com|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref> The bill was ultimately defeated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/proposal-to-end-water-fluoridation-on-health-grounds-rejected-in-d%C3%A1il-1.1588912|title=Proposal to end water fluoridation on health grounds rejected in D\u00e1il|last=O'Regan|first=Michael|website=The Irish Times|language=en|access-date=2019-12-12}}</ref>\n\nGrimes has also been publicly critical of a [[Medical cannabis|medicinal cannabis]] campaign by [[People Before Profit Alliance|People Before Profit]], specifically [[Panacea (medicine)|cure-all]] claims made by representatives of the campaign. He has particularly criticised dubious claims linking cannabis to cures for cancer and [[autism]],<ref>{{Cite news| author = Grimes, David Robert | url=https://life.spectator.co.uk/articles/the-rise-of-the-cannabis-cult-dont-believe-the-hype-about-medical-marijuana/|title=The rise of the cannabis cult: don't believe the hype about medical marijuana {{!}} Spectator Health|date=15 May 2017|work=Spectator Health|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref> saying that these positions are not supported by the evidence and could put patients at risk.\n\n=== Criticism of anti-vaccine movement and false balance ===\n\nGrimes has been particularly vocal against the [[anti-vaccine movement]], focusing on assertions by anti-[[HPV vaccines|HPV vaccine]] groups whose arguments, Grimes says, consist of \"anecdotes, emotive appeals and easily debunked assertions\", opining that \"lives of countless young men and women count on us being guided by evidence rather than rhetoric.\"<ref>{{Cite news| author = Grimes, David Robert  | url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2016/jan/11/why-is-there-opposition-hpv-vaccine-cervical-cancer|title=We know it's effective. So why is there opposition to the HPV vaccine ?|date=11 January 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 2016, following controversy around the film ''[[Vaxxed]]'', Grimes was drawn into a debate with former doctor [[Andrew Wakefield]] on Irish radio. Grimes later wrote of his reluctance to take part in the debate, and how providing Wakefield with any platform is [[false balance]].<ref>{{Cite news|author = Grimes, David Robert  | url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2016/nov/08/impartial-journalism-is-laudable-but-false-balance-is-dangerous|title=Impartial journalism is laudable. But false balance is dangerous|date=8 November 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> He was extremely critical of the decision by [[Regent's University London|Regent's University]] to host Wakefield, explaining that \"Wakefield is a long-debunked fear merchant.\"<ref>{{Cite news|date = 16 February 2016 | author = Watson, Leon | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/02/16/disgraced-antimmr-vaccine-doctor-andrew-wakefield-gets-invitation/|title=Disgraced anti\u2011MMR vaccine doctor Andrew Wakefield gets invitation to university in London|work=The Telegraph|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nGrimes was also part of a subsequent successful campaign to have screenings of the movie pulled in both London and at the European parliament.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/tomchivers/a-cinema-in-london-has-pulled-a-documentary-by-a-disgraced-a|title=A Cinema in London Has Pulled A Documentary by a Disgraced Anti-Vaccine Activist|last=Chivers|first=Tom|website=BuzzFeed|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://3menmakeatiger.blogspot.com/2017/02/andrew-wakefields-discredited-ideas-are.html|title=Three men make a tiger: Letter to President Tajani regarding EU parliament screening of anti-vaccine documentary 'Vaxxed'|last=Grimes|first=David Robert|date=1 February 2017|website=Three men make a tiger|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Advocating for evidence-based medicine ===\n\nGrimes has drawn attention to [[charlatan]]s who take advantage of vulnerable people using pseudoscience, particularly [[autistic]] people and cancer sufferers. Equally, he has been vocal about [[crowdfunding]] for dubious medical conditions and clinics, such as the [[Burzynski Clinic|Burzynkski clinic]] in [[Texas]], US, stating that while emotive, \"... raising money for such causes does not help sufferers one iota \u2013 it benefits only those with the audacity to push false hope at great expense.\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2016/aug/30/fundraising-appeals-for-the-desperately-ill-are-moving-but-evidence-is-crucial|title=Fundraising appeals for the desperately ill are moving, but evidence is crucial|last=Grimes|first=David Robert|date=30 August 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nGrimes has written at length about questionable treatments for conditions such as [[electromagnetic hypersensitivity]] which, the evidence suggests, is a psychological rather than physiological illness, criticising clinics who claim to offer cures for the ailment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2016/feb/17/electromagnetic-radiation-doesnt-make-you-ill-or-give-you-cancer-heres-why|title=Household electromagnetic radiation doesn't make you ill or give you cancer. Here's why|last=Grimes|first=David Robert|date=17 February 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.buzzfeed.com/tomchivers/a-charity-could-face-investigation-over-its-adverts-that|title=A Charity Could Face Investigation Over Its Adverts That Claim W-iFi And Mobile Phones Make People Ill|last=Chivers|first=Tom|website=BuzzFeed|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref> Grimes has been particularly critical of homoeopathy, both in academic work and in popular press, which has led to angry responses from homoeopaths.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/opinion/homeopathy-does-not-work-beyond-a-placebo-effect-1.534500|title=Homeopathy does not work beyond a placebo effect|work=The Irish Times|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mayohomeopathy.ie/index.php/david-grimes-opinion/|title=David Robert Grimes's ignorant \"Opinion\" in Irish Times \u2013 Stephen Blendell Homeopath|date=16 May 2013|work=Stephen Blendell Homeopath|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Public understanding of science ===\n\nGrimes states that a major challenge in communicating about science is not strictly information deficit but rather ideological bias, and that motivated reasoning is a vital factor to acknowledge. To support this claim, he points to the evidence that political leanings influence whether one accepts the scientific consensus on climate-change.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/2014/feb/05/denying-climate-change-scepticism-motivated-reasoning|title=Denying climate change isn't scepticism \u2013 it's 'motivated reasoning'|date=5 February 2014|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Similarly, he has argued, both in popular media and academically, that acceptance of nuclear power, gun control and vaccination is strongly influenced by ideological beliefs.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2014/aug/29/libertarian-ideology-natural-enemy-science|title=Libertarian ideology is the natural enemy of science|last=Grimes|first=David Robert|date=29 August 2014|work=The Guardian|access-date=26 July 2017|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Grimes|first=David Robert|date=26 January 2016|title=On the Viability of Conspiratorial Beliefs|journal=PLOS ONE |volume=11 |issue=1 |pages=e0147905 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0147905 |issn=1932-6203|pmc=4728076 |pmid=26812482|bibcode=2016PLoSO..1147905G}}</ref> Grimes argues that overcoming our implicit biases and gaining a better understanding of the scientific method would improve our decision making and benefit both society and individuals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/life-and-style/the-way-we-argue-now-1.1898216|title=The way we argue now|work=The Irish Times|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/society-would-benefit-from-a-better-understanding-of-what-is-and-isn-t-science-1.1458052|title=Society would benefit from a better understanding of what is and isn't science|work=The Irish Times|access-date=26 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and honours ==\nIn recognition of his efforts to present science despite hostility, Grimes was joint recipient of the 2014 Sense About Science / Nature Maddox Prize for standing up for science in the face of adversary,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://senseaboutscience.org/activities/2014-john-maddox-prize/|title=2014 John Maddox Prize \u2013 Sense about Science|website=senseaboutscience.org|access-date=21 July 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170721023505/http://senseaboutscience.org/activities/2014-john-maddox-prize/|archive-date=21 July 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and was commended by [[Cancer Research UK]] for being \"... an excellent media ambassador for CRUK, and for his efforts to dispel misconceptions in science and medicine\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cancerresearchuk.org/sites/default/files/cruk_research-engagement-prizes_2015.pdf|title=Cancer Research UK \u2013 Research Engagement Prizes}}</ref> In 2015, he was also inducted into the Dublin City University Alumni Wall for his research and outreach work.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== Published works ==\n===Popular works===\n====Books====\n* {{cite book |title=The Irrational Ape: Why Flawed Logic Puts us all at Risk and How Critical Thinking Can Save the World |first=David Robert |last=Grimes |publisher=[[Simon and Schuster]] |date=5 September 2019 |url= {{Google books|gXN5DwAAQBAJ|plainurl=yes}} |via=[[Google books]]}}\n<!--====Articles====\n*\n===Scholarly work===\n====Reviews====\n* \n====Research articles====\n*-->\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160221233502/http://users.ox.ac.uk/~donc0074/ Grimes staff page] at [[University of Oxford|Oxford]]. \n* [http://www.davidrobertgrimes.com/ Grimes's personal blog].\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Grimes, David Robert}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Date of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Dublin City University]]\n[[Category:British sceptics]]\n[[Category:British physicists]]\n[[Category:Critics of alternative medicine]]\n[[Category:Irish physicists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin (city)]]\n", "name_user": "MissyCa", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(Added)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Robert_Grimes"}
{"title_page": "Nizhny Novgorod", "text_new": "{{short description|City in Nizhny Novgorod Oblast, Russia}}\n{{For|other cities named Novgorod|Novgorod (disambiguation)}}\n{{Distinguish|Veliky Novgorod }}\n{{Infobox Russian inhabited locality\n| en_name                 = Nizhny Novgorod\n| ru_name                 = \u041d\u0438\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\n| loc_name1               = \n| loc_lang1               = \n| loc_name2               = \n| loc_lang2               = \n| loc_name3               = \n| loc_lang3               = \n| settlement_type         = [[Administrative centre]]\n| other_name              = Gorky\n| other_lang              = \n| image_skyline           = Nizhny Novgorod Montage (2016).png\n| image_caption           = '''Clockwise:''' [[Dmitrievskaya Tower]] of the [[Nizhny Novgorod Kremlin|Kremlin]], [[Chkalov Stairs]], [[Nizhny Novgorod Fair|the Fair]], [[GAZ]], Minin and Pozharsky Monument, [[Alexander Nevsky Cathedral, Nizhny Novgorod|Saint Alexander Nevsky cathedral]] and [[Nizhny Novgorod Stadium|stadium]].\n| image_map               = {{Maplink|frame=yes|plain=y|frame-width=325|frame-height=325|zoom=9|frame-lat=56.3269|frame-long=44.007|id=Q891|title=Nizhny Novgorod}}\n| mapsize                         = 230px\n| pushpin_map                     = European Russia#Europe\n| pushpin_relief                  = 1\n| map_caption             = Nizhny Novgorod in Russia\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = [[Russia]]\n| coordinates             = {{coord|56|19|37|N|44|00|27|E|display=inline,title}}\n| image_flag              = Flag of Nizhny Novgorod.svg{{!}}border\n| flag_caption            = \n| image_coa               = Coat of Arms of Nizhny Novgorod.svg\n| coa_caption             = [[Coat of arms of Nizhny Novgorod|Coat of arms]]\n| anthem                  = \n| anthem_ref              = \n| holiday                 = 3rd Saturday of August\n| holiday_ref             = <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nn.ru/news/more/vnov_okonchatelno_den_goroda_v_nizhnem_novgorode_perenesli_na_avgust/66097765/|title=\u0412\u043d\u043e\u0432\u044c \u043e\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0447\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e. \u0414\u0435\u043d\u044c \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0432 \u041d\u0438\u0436\u043d\u0435\u043c \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0441\u043b\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442 \u2014 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 NN.RU|date=2019-05-22|website=www.nn.ru|language=ru|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n<!-- administrative status -->\n| federal_subject         = [[Nizhny Novgorod Oblast]]\n| federal_subject_ref     = <ref name=\"Ref818\" />\n| adm_district_jur        = \n| adm_district_jur_ref    = \n| adm_inhabloc_jur        = [[city of federal subject significance|city of oblast significance]] of Nizhny Novgorod\n| adm_inhabloc_jur_ref    = <ref name=\"Ref818\" />\n| adm_citydistrict_jur    = \n| adm_citydistrict_type   = \n| adm_citydistrict_jur_ref = \n| adm_selsoviet_jur       = \n| adm_selsoviet_type      = \n| adm_selsoviet_jur_ref   = \n| capital_of              = \n| capital_of_ref          = \n| adm_ctr_of1             = Nizhny Novgorod Oblast\n| adm_ctr_of1_ref         = <ref name=\"Ref818\" />\n| adm_ctr_of2             = city of oblast significance of Nizhny Novgorod\n| adm_ctr_of2_ref         = <ref name=\"Ref818\" />\n| adm_ctr_of3             = \n| adm_ctr_of3_ref         = \n| inhabloc_cat            = City\n| inhabloc_cat_ref        = <ref name=\"Ref818\" />\n| inhabloc_type           = \n| inhabloc_type_ref       = \n<!-- municipal status -->\n| mun_district_jur        = \n| mun_district_jur_ref    = \n| urban_okrug_jur         = Nizhny Novgorod Urban Okrug\n| urban_okrug_jur_ref     = <ref name=\"Ref825\" />\n| urban_settlement_jur    = \n| urban_settlement_jur_ref = \n| rural_settlement_jur    = \n| rural_settlement_jur_ref = \n| inter_settlement_territory = \n| inter_settlement_territory_ref = \n| mun_admctr_of1          = Nizhny Novgorod Urban Okrug \n| mun_admctr_of1_ref      = <ref name=\"Ref825\"/> \n| mun_admctr_of2          = \n| mun_admctr_of2_ref      = \n| leader_title            = [[Mayor of Nizhny Novgorod|Mayor]]\n| leader_title_ref        = <ref name=\"HeadTitle\">Charter of Nizhny Novgorod, Article&nbsp;26.1.2</ref>\n| leader_name             = [[Vladimir Panov]]\n| leader_name_ref         = <ref name=\"HeadName\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.the-village.ru/village/city/news-city/297962-merom-nizhnego-novgoroda-izbran-vladimir-panov|script-title=ru:\u041c\u044d\u0440\u043e\u043c \u041d\u0438\u0436\u043d\u0435\u0433\u043e \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0438\u0437\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u041f\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432|last=|first=|date=|work=The Village|access-date=2018-01-17|language=ru}}</ref>\n| representative_body     = [[City Duma of Nizhny Novgorod|City Duma]]\n| representative_body_ref = <ref name=\"Legis\">Charter of Nizhny Novgorod, Article&nbsp;26.1.1</ref>\n<!-- statistics -->\n| elevation_m             = \n| area_km2                = 460\n| area_km2_ref            = <ref name=\"AboutCity\">Official website of Nizhny Novgorod.  [http://www.admgor.nnov.ru/references/nn.html Overview of the city] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090430163414/http://www.admgor.nnov.ru/references/nn.html |date=April 30, 2009 }} {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n| pop_2010census          = 1250619\n| pop_2010census_rank     = 5th\n| pop_2010census_ref      = <ref name=\"2010Census\" />\n| pop_latest              = \n| pop_latest_date         = \n| pop_latest_ref          = \n| population_demonym      = \n| time_zone_ref           = \n<!-- history -->\n| established_date        = 1221\n| established_title       = \n| established_date_ref    = <ref name=\"found\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nizhnynovgorod.com/welcome/history/|title=Founding of Nizhny Novgorod|publisher=nizhnynovgorod.com|access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref>\n| current_cat_date        = 1221\n| current_cat_date_ref    = <ref name=\"found\" />\n| abolished_date          = \n| abolished_date_ref      = \n<!-- misc -->\n| postal_codes            = 603000-603999\n| postal_codes_ref        = \n| dialing_codes           = 831\n| dialing_codes_ref       = <ref name=\"codes\">{{cite web|url=http://adm.nnov.ru/en/contacts/|title=Contacts|publisher=adm.nnov.ru|access-date=2016-08-15}}</ref>\n| website                 = http://admgor.nnov.ru/\n|date=January 2019}}\n'''Nizhny Novgorod''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|n|\u026a|\u0292|n|i|_|\u02c8|n|\u0252|v|\u0261|\u0259|r|\u0252|d}} {{respell|NIZH|nee|_|NOV|g\u0259|rod}};<ref>\n{{cite book|last=Wells|first=John C.|year=2008|title=Longman Pronunciation Dictionary|edition=3rd|publisher=Longman|isbn=978-1-4058-8118-0}}</ref> {{lang-rus|links=no|\u041d\u0438\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434|a=|p=\u02c8n\u02b2i\u0290n\u02b2\u026aj \u02c8nov\u0261\u0259r\u0259t}}), colloquially shortened to '''Nizhny''', is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|city]] in [[Russia]] and the [[administrative center]] (capital<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nischni-nowgorod.ru/?page_id=13|title=\u041d\u0438\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434 \u2013 \u0421\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u041f\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043b\u0436\u044c\u044f \u0438 \"\u043a\u0430\u0440\u043c\u0430\u043d \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438\" {{!}}  www.Nischni-Nowgorod.ru|website=www.nischni-nowgorod.ru|language=de|access-date=2017-07-31}}</ref>) of [[Volga Federal District]] and [[Nizhny Novgorod Oblast]]. From 1932 to 1990, it was known as '''Gorky''' ({{lang|ru|\u0413\u043e\u0440\u044c\u043a\u0438\u0439}}, {{IPA-ru|\u02c8\u0261or\u02b2k\u02b2\u026aj|IPA}}),<ref name=\"PrevName2\">Decree of October 22, 1990, Article&nbsp;1</ref> after the writer [[Maxim Gorky]], who was born there.\n\nThe city is an important economic, transportation, scientific, educational and cultural center in Russia and the vast [[Volga-Vyatka economic region]], and is the main center of river tourism in Russia. In the historic part of the city there are many universities, theaters, museums and churches. Nizhny Novgorod is located about {{cvt|400|km|round=50}} east of [[Moscow]], where the [[Oka River]] empties into the [[Volga]]. Population: {{ru-census|p2010=1,250,619|p2002=1,311,252|p1989=1,438,133}}\n\nThe city was founded in 4 February 1221<ref>{{cite book| author = Vladimir Kuchin | chapter = | chapter-url = | format = | url =  | title = \u0414\u0435\u0441\u044f\u0442\u044c \u0432\u0435\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u041d\u0438\u0436\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f. 1152\u20142018 | orig-year = | agency =  | edition =   |location=  |year= 2018 |publisher= \u0418\u0437\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0440\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f |at=  |volume= 3 |issue = | pages = | page =  | series =  | isbn = 978-5-4490-6270-3| ref = }}</ref> by Prince [[Yuri II of Vladimir]]. In 1612 [[Kuzma Minin]] and Prince [[Dmitry Pozharsky]] organized an army for the liberation of [[Moscow]] from the [[Polish\u2013Muscovite War (1605\u201318)|Poles]]. In 1817 Nizhny Novgorod became a [[Nizhny Novgorod Fair|great trade center]] of the [[Russian Empire]]. In 1896 at a [[Nizhny Novgorod Fair|fair]], an [[All-Russia Exhibition 1896|All-Russia Exhibition]] was organized. During the [[Soviet Union|Soviet period]], the city turned into an important industrial center. In particular, the [[Gorky Automobile Plant]] was constructed in this period. Then the city was given the nickname \"Russian [[Detroit]]\". During [[World War II]], Gorky became the biggest provider of military equipment to the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]]. Due to this, the [[Luftwaffe]] constantly [[Bombing of Gorky in World War II|bombed the city]] from the air. The majority of the German bombs fell in the area of the Gorky Automobile Plant. Although almost all the production sites of the plant were completely destroyed, the citizens of Gorky reconstructed the factory after 100 days.\n\nAfter the war, Gorky became a \"[[closed city]]\" and remained one until after the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]] in 1990. At that time, the city was renamed Nizhny Novgorod once again. In 1985, the [[Nizhny Novgorod Metro]] was opened. In 2016, [[Vladimir Putin]] opened the new 70th Anniversary of Victory Plant which is part of the [[Almaz-Antey]] Air and Space Defence Corporation.\n\nThe [[Nizhny Novgorod Kremlin|Kremlin]] \u2013 the [[Historic centre of Nizhny Novgorod|main center]] of the city \u2013 contains the main government agencies of the city and the Volga Federal District. The [[demonym]] for a Nizhny Novgorod resident is \"\u043d\u0438\u0436\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0435\u0446\" (''nizhegorodets'') for male or \"\u043d\u0438\u0436\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043a\u0430\" (''nizhegorodka'') for female, rendered in English as ''Nizhegorodian''. ''Novgorodian'' is inappropriate; it refers to a resident of [[Veliky Novgorod]], in [[Northwestern Federal District|northwestern Russia]].\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|History of Nizhny Novgorod|Timeline of Nizhny Novgorod}}\n\n===Name===\nOriginally the name was just Novgorod (\"Newtown\"), but to distinguish it from the other, older and well-known [[Veliky Novgorod|Novgorod]] (Veliky Novgorod) to the west, the city was commonly called \"Novgorod of the Lower lands\", or  \"Lower Newtown\". This land was named \"lower\" ([[:wikt:\u043d\u0438\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0439|''nizhniy'' or ''ni\u017enij'' (\u043d\u0438\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0439)]]), even though it is actually higher in altitude than Veliky Novgorod, because it is situated downstream of other Russian cities such as Moscow, [[Vladimir, Russia|Vladimir]] and [[Murom]].\n\n===Seat of medieval princes===\n{{Main|Principality of Nizhny Novgorod-Suzdal}}\nThe city traces its origin from a small Russian wooden hillfort that was founded by Grand Duke [[Yuri II of Vladimir|Yuri&nbsp;II]] in 1221 at the [[Spit of Nizhny Novgorod|confluence]] of two of the most important rivers in his principality, the [[Volga River|Volga]] and [[Oka River|Oka]] rivers. It marked the eastern extreme of [[East Slavs|East Slavic]] settlement until the end of the medieval period, with Russian expansion eastward delayed until the \n[[Russo-Kazan Wars|capture of Kazan]] in 1552. \nIts independent existence of the medieval fort was threatened by the continuous [[Mordvins|Mordvin]] attacks against it; the major attempt made by forces under [[Purgaz]] in April 1229 was repulsed, but after the death of Yuri&nbsp;II on March&nbsp;4, 1238 at the [[Battle of the Sit River]], the Mongols occupied the fortress. Later a major stronghold for border protection, Nizhny Novgorod fortress took advantage of a natural moat formed by the two rivers.\n\nAlong with [[Moscow]] and [[Tver]], Nizhny Novgorod was among several newly founded towns that escaped [[Mongol invasion of Russia|Mongol devastation]] on account of their insignificance, but grew into (great) centers in vassalic Russian political life during the period of the [[Tatar Yoke]]. With the agreement of the Mongol Khan, Nizhny Novgorod was incorporated into the [[Vladimir-Suzdal|Vladimir-Suzdal Principality]] in 1264. After 86 years its importance further increased when the seat of the powerful [[Suzdal]] Principality was moved here from [[Gorodets, Nizhny Novgorod Oblast|Gorodets]] in 1350. Grand Duke [[Dmitry Konstantinovich]] (1323\u20131383) sought to make his capital a rival worthy of Moscow; he built a stone citadel and several churches and was a patron of historians. The earliest extant [[manuscript]] of the [[Russian Primary Chronicle]], the ''[[Laurentian Codex]]'', was written for him by the local monk Laurentius in 1377.\n\n===Strongest fortress of the Grand Duchy of Moscow===\n[[File:Appeal of Minin.jpg|thumb|left|[[Kuzma Minin]] appeals to the people of Nizhny Novgorod to raise a volunteer army against the [[Polish People|Poles]] (painting by [[Konstantin Makovsky]], 1896).]]After the city's incorporation into the [[Grand Duchy of Moscow]] in 1392, the local princes took the name [[Shuisky]] and settled in Moscow, where they were prominent at the court and briefly ascended the throne in the person of [[Vasili IV of Russia|Vasily&nbsp;IV]]. After being burnt by the powerful [[Crimean Tatars|Crimean Tatar]] chief [[Edigu]] in 1408, Nizhny Novgorod was restored and regarded by the Muscovites primarily as a great stronghold in [[Russo-Kazan Wars|their wars]] against the [[Khanate of Kazan|Tatars of Kazan]]. The enormous red-brick [[Nizhny Novgorod Kremlin|kremlin]], one of the strongest and earliest preserved citadels in Russia, was built in 1508\u20131511 under the supervision of Peter the [[Italy|Italian]]. The fortress was strong enough to withstand Tatar sieges in 1520 and 1536.\n\nIn 1612, the so-called \"national militia\", gathered by a local merchant, [[Kuzma Minin]], and commanded by [[Knyaz]] [[Dmitry Pozharsky]] expelled the [[Poland|Polish]] troops from Moscow, thus putting an end to the \"[[Time of Troubles]]\" and establishing the rule of the [[Romanov]] dynasty. The main square in front of the [[Nizhny Novgorod Kremlin|Kremlin]] is named after [[Kuzma Minin|Minin]] and [[Dmitry Pozharsky|Pozharsky]], although it is locally known simply as Minin Square. Minin's remains are buried in the citadel. (In commemoration of these events, on October 21, 2005, an exact copy of the [[Monument to Minin and Pozharsky|Red Square statue]] of Minin and Pozharsky was placed in front of St John the Baptist Church, which is believed to be the place from where the call to the people had been proclaimed.)\n\nIn the course of the following century, the city prospered commercially and was chosen by the [[Stroganov]]s (the wealthiest merchant family of Russia) as a base for their operations. A particular style of [[Russian architecture|architecture]] and icon painting, known as the [[Stroganov style]], developed there at the turn of the 17th and 18th centuries.\n\nThe historical [[coat of arms of Nizhny Novgorod]] in 1781 was a red deer with black horns and hooves on a white field. The modern coat of arms from 2006 is the same, with a ribbon of [[order of Lenin]] and gold crown from above.\n\n===Great trade center===\n[[File:Nizhny Novgorod Fair 1903.jpg|thumb|Main building of the [[All-Russia exhibition 1896|Great Russian Fair]], 19th-century postcard|alt=|left]]{{See also|Nizhny Novgorod Fair|All-Russia Exhibition 1896}}\nIn 1817, the [[Nizhny Novgorod Fair|Makaryev Fair]], one of the liveliest in the world, was transferred to Nizhny Novgorod, and started to attract millions of visitors annually. By the mid-19th century, the city was firmly established as the [[trade]] capital of the [[Russian Empire]]. The world's first radio receiver by engineer [[Alexander Stepanovich Popov|Alexander Popov]] and the world's first [[hyperboloid structure|hyperboloid tower]] and lattice shell-coverings by engineer [[Vladimir Shukhov]] were demonstrated at the [[All-Russia exhibition 1896|All-Russia industrial and art exhibition in Nizhny Novgorod]] in 1896. According to official Imperial Russian statistics the population of Nizhny Novgorod as of 14 January 1913 was 97,000.\n\nThe largest industrial enterprise was the [[Sormovsky City District|Sormovo]] Iron Works which was connected by the company's own railway to Moscow station in the Lower Area of Nizhny Novgorod. The private Moscow to Kazan Railway Company's station was in the Upper Area of the city. Other industries gradually developed, and by the start of the 20th century the city was also a first-rank industrial hub. [[Henry Ford]] helped build a large truck and tractor plant ([[GAZ]]) in the late 1920s, sending engineers and mechanics, including future labour leader [[Walter Reuther]].\n\n===Soviet era===\n[[File:9th May. Day of the German surrender. Gorky 1.jpg|thumb|[[Victory Day (9 May)|Victory Day]] on the [[Minin and Pozharsky Square]], 9 May 1945|alt=|left]]\n\nThere were no permanent bridges over the Volga or Oka before the [[October Revolution]] in 1917. Temporary bridges were built during the trade fair. The first bridge over the Volga was started by the Moscow\u2013Kazan Railway Company in 1914, but only finished in the [[Soviet Era]] when the railway to [[Kotelnich]] was opened for service in 1927.\n\n[[Maxim Gorky]] was born in Nizhny Novgorod in 1868 as Alexey Maximovich Peshkov. In his novels he described the dismal life of the city [[proletariat]]. When he returned to the [[Soviet Union]] in 1932 on the invitation of [[Joseph Stalin]], the city was renamed '''Gorky'''. The city bore Gorky's name until 1990. His childhood home is preserved as a museum, known as the Kashirin House, after Alexey's grandfather who owned the place.\n\n{{Main|Bombing of Gorky in World War II}}\n\nDuring [[World War II]], from 1941 to 1943, Gorky was subjected to air raids and bombardments by [[Nazi Germany|Germany]]. The Germans tried to destroy the city industry because it was the main supplier of military equipment to the front. These attacks became the most powerful in the entire World War II in the rear of the [[Soviet Union]].\n\nDuring much of the Soviet era, the city was [[closed city|closed]] to foreigners to safeguard the security of Soviet military research and production facilities, even though it was a popular stopping point for Soviet tourists traveling up and down the Volga in tourist boats. Unusually for a Soviet city of that size, even street maps were not available for sale until the mid-1970s. In 1970, by the Decree of the [[Presidium of the Supreme Soviet|Presidium of the Supreme Soviet of the USSR]], the city was awarded the [[Order of Lenin]]. [[M\u00e1ty\u00e1s R\u00e1kosi]], communist leader of [[Hungary]], died there in 1971. November 20, 1985 in the city was launched the first section of the [[Nizhny Novgorod Metro|metro]]. The [[physicist]] and [[Nobel prize|Nobel laureate]] [[Andrei Sakharov]] was exiled there during 1980\u20131986 to limit his contacts with foreigners. An end to the \"closed\" status of the city accompanied the reinstatement of the city's original name in 1990.<ref name=\"PrevName2\"/>\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:NN Minin and Pozharsky Square view 08-2016.jpg|[[Dmitrievskaya Tower|Dmitrovskaya tower]] of the [[Nizhny Novgorod Kremlin|Kremlin]]\nFile:NN Stroganov Church 08-2016 img2.jpg|[[Church of the Nativity of the Blessed Virgin Mary, Nizhny Novgorod|Church of the Nativity]]\nFile:NN Spit from Lower-Volga Embankment 12-2018.jpg 04.jpg|The [[Spit of Nizhny Novgorod|Spit]] (confluence of [[Oka River|Oka]] and [[Volga River|Volga Rivers]])\nFile:NN BolPokrovskaya view towards the Kremlin 08-2016.jpg|[[Bolshaya Pokrovskaya Street]]\n</gallery>\n\n==Administrative and municipal status==\nNizhny Novgorod is the [[administrative center]] (capital) of [[Volga Federal District]] and [[Nizhny Novgorod Oblast]].<ref name=\"Ref818\">Law #184-Z</ref> Within the [[subdivisions of Russia#Administrative divisions|framework of administrative divisions]], it is, together with one [[urban-type settlement|resort settlement]] and twelve [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural localities]], incorporated as the '''[[city of federal subject significance|city of oblast significance]] of Nizhny Novgorod'''\u2014an administrative unit with the status equal to that of the [[administrative divisions of Nizhny Novgorod Oblast|districts]].<ref name=\"Ref818\"/> As a [[Municipal divisions of Russia|municipal division]], the city of oblast significance of Nizhny Novgorod is incorporated as '''Nizhny Novgorod Urban Okrug'''.<ref name=\"Ref825\">Law #205-Z</ref>\nIn December 2011, [[Marat Safin]] was elected to the Russian Parliament as a member of [[Vladimir Putin]]'s [[United Russia]] Party, representing Nizhny Novgorod.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://vote.duma.gov.ru/vote/79982|title=\u04141 (2 \u0447\u0442\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435) \u0424\u0417 \u2116186614-6 \"\u041e \u043c\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0445 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u0434\u0435\u0439\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u043b\u0438\u0446, \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u043a \u043d\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044e \u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u0430\u0433\u0430\u044e\u0449\u0438\u0445 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432 \u0438 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0434 \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430, \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0432 \u0438 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0431\u043e\u0434 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0430\u043d \u0420\u0424\" \u2013 \u0421\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043c\u0430 \u0430\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430 \u0440\u0435\u0437\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0433\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439 \u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0430\u0441\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f\u0445 \u0413\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0414\u0443\u043c\u044b|publisher=Vote.duma.gov.ru|date=19 December 2012|accessdate=18 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==City layout and divisions==\n{{Further|Administrative divisions of Nizhny Novgorod}}\n[[File:Location Map of Rayons NN 2020.png|right|thumb|250px| Administrative divisions of Nizhny Novgorod]]\n\nNizhny Novgorod is divided by the [[Oka River]] into two distinct parts. The Upper City ({{lang-ru|\u041d\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0440\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c}}, ''Nagornaya chast'', ''Mountainous part'') is located on the hilly eastern (right) bank of the Oka. It includes three of the eight city districts into which the city is administratively divided:\n\n# <span style=\"color:#FECCCC;\">\u2588</span> [[Nizhegorodsky City District, Nizhny Novgorod|Nizhegorodsky]] (the [[Nizhny Novgorod Kremlin|Kremlin]], the historical and administrative center of the city);\n# <span style=\"color:#CCFEFE;\">\u2588</span> [[Prioksky City District|Prioksky]]\n# <span style=\"color:#F5F5F5;\">\u2588</span> [[Sovetsky City District, Nizhny Novgorod|Sovetsky]]\n\nThe Lower City ({{lang-ru|\u0417\u0430\u0440\u0435\u0447\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0447\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c}}, ''Zarechnaya chast'', ''Over river part'') occupies the low (western) side of the Oka, and includes five city districts:\n# <span style=\"color:#FECCFE;\">\u2588</span> [[Avtozavodsky City District, Nizhny Novgorod|Avtozavodsky]] (built around the [[GAZ|Gorky Automobile Plant]]);\n# <span style=\"color:#CCCCFE;\">\u2588</span> [[Kanavinsky City District|Kanavinsky]] (the site of the [[Nizhny Novgorod Fair]] and the location of the [[Nizhny Novgorod railway station|main train station]]);\n# <span style=\"color:#CCFECC;\">\u2588</span> [[Leninsky City District, Nizhny Novgorod|Leninsky]].\n# <span style=\"color:#CCCCCC;\">\u2588</span> [[Moskovsky City District, Nizhny Novgorod|Moskovsky]] (home of the [[Sokol plant|Sokol Aircraft Plant]] and [[Sormovo (airfield)|its airfield]]);\n# <span style=\"color:#FEFECC;\">\u2588</span> [[Sormovsky City District|Sormovsky]] (where [[Krasnoye Sormovo]] and the [[Krasnoye Sormovo Factory No. 112|Volga Shipyard]] are located);\nAll of today's lower city was annexed by Nizhny Novgorod in 1929\u20131931.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{See also|Jewish community of Nizhny Novgorod}}\n*Population: {{ru-census|p2010=1,250,619|p2002=1,311,252|p1989=1,438,133}}\n*Births (2009): 12,934\n*Deaths (2009): 20,987\n\nNizhny Novgorod is the fifth-largest [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|city]] in [[Russia]], ranking after [[Moscow]], [[Saint Petersburg|St Petersburg]], [[Novosibirsk]], and [[Yekaterinburg]]. For a long time it was the third-largest city after Moscow and St Petersburg.\n\n==Geograph\u0443 and climate==\n[[File:Central Nizhny Novgorod.png|thumb|Historic city center|alt=]]\n===Time===\nThe area operates in what is referred to in international standards as [[Moscow Standard Time]] (MSK), which is 3 hours ahead of [[UTC]], or [[UTC+3]]. [[Daylight saving time]] is no longer observed.\n\n===Climate===\nIn 1834 the first weather station was opened in Nizhny Novgorod. A century later it transformed into Gorky Hydrometeorological service, then since 1978 it is known as the Higher Volga hydrometeorology and natural habitat control department.\n\nThe [[climate]] in the region is continental, specifically [[humid continental]] (''Dfb''), and it is similar to the [[climate of Moscow|climate in Moscow]], although colder in winter, which lasts from late November until late March with a permanent snow cover. Average temperatures range from {{convert|+19|C}} in July to {{convert|-9|C}} in January. Average annual temperature is {{convert|+4.8|C}}, wind speed 2.8 m/s, air humidity 76%.\n\nNizhny receives on average 1 775 hours of sunshine a year. The maximum duration of daylight is in June (17 hours 44 minutes), the minimum - in December (6 hours 52 minutes). Overcast is often reported in winter: 75 to 80% of the time the sky is covered in clouds, while it's only 49 to 56% in April through to August. In autumn and winter the overcast is usually in the mornings, then the sky clears in the afternoon. In spring and summer, on the contrary, it is clear in the mornings, while towards midday clouds cluster ('[[cumulus cloud]]'), and disappear towards the evening.\n\nIn spring temperatures set above zero around April 5th and stay until the end of October. On average precipitation comes at 653 mm per year, mostly in July and least of all in March. Generally, 180 days out of 365 enjoy some form of precipitation. [[Snow]] first comes in October but the blanket of snow insulates the ground at November-end and melts mid-April. As a rule, the air temperature in winter ranges from {{convert|-10|C}} to {{convert|-20|C}}. A storm rarely takes place in winter here (a few dates to mention are 27 November 1940, 30 November 1951, 14 February 1960, and 3 December 1962). In [[spring (season)|spring]] there's less precipitation than in other seasons. Spring flies by as snow melts in the second half of March and is normally gone by the end of April. [[Summer]] comes at the beginning of June, when temperature sets around +15. Maximum heat can be observed towards the third decade of July. Average temperatures range from {{convert|+15|C}} to {{convert|+20|C}}. A maximum temperature of {{convert|+38.2|C}} was recorded during the [[2010 Northern Hemisphere summer heat waves]]. Summer [[rain]] is short but intense, with strong [[wind]]. In September temperature starts to drop and gets below {{convert|+10|C}} in mid-20s of the month. It rains often and heavily in [[autumn]], the sky is overcast.\n\n{{Clear}}{{Weather box\n|location=Nizhny Novgorod\n|metric first=yes\n|single line=yes\n|Jan record high C=5.7\n|Feb record high C=7.0\n|Mar record high C=17.3\n|Apr record high C= 26.3\n|May record high C = 32.5\n|Jun record high C = 36.3\n|Jul record high C = 38.2\n|Aug record high C = 38.0\n|Sep record high C = 31.0\n|Oct record high C = 24.2\n|Nov record high C = 13.8\n|Dec record high C = 8.5\n|year record high C = 38.2\n|Jan high C = -5.9\n|Feb high C = -5.3\n|Mar high C = 1.1\n|Apr high C = 10.9\n|May high C = 18.7\n|Jun high C = 22.6\n|Jul high C = 24.7\n|Aug high C = 22.1\n|Sep high C = 15.6\n|Oct high C = 8.0\n|Nov high C = -0.5\n|Dec high C = -4.7\n|year high C = 8.9\n|Jan mean C = -8.9\n|Feb mean C = -8.7\n|Mar mean C = -2.6\n|Apr mean C = 6.1\n|May mean C = 12.9\n|Jun mean C = 17.2\n|Jul mean C = 19.4\n|Aug mean C = 16.9\n|Sep mean C = 11.1\n|Oct mean C = 4.7\n|Nov mean C = -2.8\n|Dec mean C = -7.4\n|year mean C = 4.8\n|Jan low C = -11.6\n|Feb low C = -11.7\n|Mar low C = -5.8\n|Apr low C = 2.1\n|May low C = 7.9\n|Jun low